<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I think it's safe to assume that US military forces will be in Iraq for awhile but I'm not convinced that they'll be staying forever.  Iraq will need help in everyway for a long time after the war and the time table on the presence of US forces there probably depends on how well the new government in Iraq functions.  Even though everyone likes to call this war an imperialist act where we will rule Iraq with an iron fist, I'm just not convinced.  In any case, I don't see how it could be any worse than being ruled by Saddam.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=talche>Talche</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/29/03 3:45 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=360.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: War for Oil</span><hr size=1> I agree that a US controlled puppet government will be no worse for the Iraqi people than Saddam, (he is without doubt a cruel and arrogant man and no sane person will be sorry to see him go.)<br>
<br>
The real danger of this course of action for the West is the risk of civil war in Iraq and resurgent terrorism throughout the Middle East.<br>
<br>
My guess is that the *Coalition* leaders expect this to happen, but are willing to put up with it and take measures to contain it. (After all what's really at stake here? No less than the survival of *our way of life* in the West, our *civilisation*!)<br>
<br>
The real stumbling block is going to be when the oil is running out <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>everywhere</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, which it inevitably will within our lifetimes.  What happens then?<br>
<br>
Maybe by then there will be viable alternative energy strategies available, maybe not.  Either way we will have to expect dramatic (and no doubt painful) changes to *our way of life*, social restructuring on a scale we can't even begin to imagine.<br>
<br>
Or maybe even this fragile *castle in the air* that we all live in and take for granted will simply start to crumble. I take it you will have heard how the history of Easter Island is now often interpreted as a chilling prophecy of *the human future*.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/lostempires/easter/images/movesslide01.jpg"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
