<br>
I wonder if in 500 years or so people will be saying of us the equivalent of “Didn’t they realise that if they cut down all the trees there’d be no more trees” <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :purpleunhappy --><img src=http://www.smilies-world.de/Smilies/Smilies_klein_1/Smilies_klein_1_1/shakemitkopf.gif ALT=":purpleunhappy"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Our whole Hi-tech society and high population density depends on readily available, inexpensive, and easily utilised energy. This affects areas that most people don’t even think about!<br>
<br>
For example, if diesel went up to £50/Gallon, not only would it be very expensive to travel. Farms would not be able to grow food any more; the great grain producing areas of the planet would revert to grazing. For the rich, this would be not too much of a problem, but huge numbers of people would go hungry! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
The tragedy is that no real effort may be made to develop large scale alternatives to Oil, Gas and coal until after supplies are threatened. By then we may risk simply not having the resources to do the necessary development!<br>
<br>
For my part I would like to see the mines closed and the wells capped ASAP and Nuclear (or whatever) alternatives developed with the greatest of urgency. This is not just because I think oil and coal are nasty polluting fuels. Much more importantly, its because I want to be able to give somebody else a chance!<br>
<br>
If our civilisation fails, I want to leave enough fossil fuels in the ground so that at some point in the future somebody else may have a chance to succeed where we failed. Without access to fossil fuels, a future emerging civilisation will never be able to pass through the agrarian phase (Greece or Rome, but nothing any more sophisticated). I feel we should give the future a chance to succeed if we fail!<br>
<br>
Dusty<br>
